What if every neural network prediction came with a certificate of trust?

That’s the core of our latest #VibeCodeArena challenge:
Design a deep learning architecture where every inference is accompanied by a mechanically verified formal proof of correctness, consistency, and safety.

No more heuristic confidence scores. No more “trust me”—just provable guarantees.

What this looks like in practice:

• A neural core for the predictions.
• A reasoning layer that translates latent representations into constraints.
• A proof generator that emits structured proof artifacts.
• A verifier that mechanically checks each proof before the inference is accepted.

If the proof fails, the inference doesn’t get deployed. End of story.

Training strategy:

• Joint optimization of prediction quality and proof verifiability.
• Loss functions that reward proofs that are both correct and minimal.
• A curriculum that scales from simple logical invariants to deep safety guarantees.

Why this matters:

The AI community talks about trust and safety, but few solutions have mathematical evidence at inference time. This challenge bridges deep learning with formal methods—transforming ambiguous neural outputs into verifiable claims.

For anyone building AI at scale—especially in regulated domains— this is new baseline for accountability.

If your model can’t explain its answer to a theorem prover, is it really ready for the real world?

